{"id": 232085382, "title": "Up for sail! Iconic windmill from the film Chitty Chitty Bang Bang hits the market for \u00a37million...", "text": "Up for sail! Iconic windmill from the film Chitty Chitty Bang Bang hits the market for \u00a37million after dropping in price by \u00a32m Unusual property in Turville, Bucks was home to the Potts family in 1968 classic By Sam Lawley Published: 15:58 BST, 9 June 2024 | Updated: 16:06 BST, 9 June 2024 e-mail View comments The famous windmill from the 1968 classic film Chitty Chitty Bang Bang has plummeted in price by a whopping \u00a32million after failing to find a buyer. The property, which was the home of the Potts family in the much-loved movie, is now on the market, along with a main flint house on site, for the modest sum of \u00a37million. The unusual home is known as Cobstone Mill and is found in the affluent Buckinghamshire village of Turville, around 20 minutes from High Wycombe and surrounded by stunning countryside views. The complex boasts six bedrooms and four bathrooms and is listed online as having become 'unexpectedly re-available'. Following the huge success of the film, which starred Dick Van Dyke and Sally Ann Howes, the property was bought by the actress Hayley Mills and her film director husband Roy Boulting. The famous windmill (pictured) from the 1968 classic film Chitty Chitty Bang Bang has dropped in price by a whopping \u00a32million after failing to find a buyer The windmill pictured in the movie. The property, which was the home of the Potts' family in the much-loved movie, is now on the market, along with a main flint house on site, for the modest sum of \u00a37million The structure is called Cobstone Mill and is found in the affluent Buckinghamshire village of Turville Together, they restored the run down property to its former glory. It was then sold on, with future owners including David Brown, the late former owner of Aston Martin. Read More Iconic windmill from the film Chitty Chitty Bang Bang is for sale for \u00a39million The Grade II listed windmill's exterior sails have been fully restored by the current owner in the two years. The original working mill is still visible inside, alongside a winding staircase leading from the ground floor, where there is the main reception room. The staircase leads to two bedrooms on the first and second floors, with views across the Hambleden Valley. Cobstone Mill is believed to have been used to grind cereal until 1873 and, as well as playing a starring role in Chitty Chitty Bang Bang, has featured in a number of television shows. Alongside the windmill, there is a separate main house on the property and almost 37 acres of land, which includes a swimming pool and outbuildings. The main flint house has a grand double-height drawing room with floor to ceiling doors that open on to a large terrace overlooking a sheltered swimming pool. The property has six bedrooms in total - including the bedroom in the separate garage annexe - and currently spreads across almost 2,600 square feet. Planning consent was granted in 2016 to substantially extend the main house. The property is around 50 miles from central London and is around five miles from Saunderton and Henley-on Thames train stations. Alongside the windmill, there is a separate main house on the property with an outdoor swimming pool The stunning property has been restored, with the original working mill still visible inside The exterior sails of the iconic windmill have been fully restored by the current owners The property is around 50 miles from central London and is around five miles from Saunderton and Henley-on Thames train stations The main flint house has a grand double-height drawing room with floor to ceiling doors that open on to a large terrace Planning consent was granted in 2016 to substantially extend the main house The home has convenient road links and rail options, leading to London, Heathrow and Oxford. Set in a peaceful pocket of Buckinghamshire, t